HTML:

index.html

1. Default name of a websites homepage
2. First page users see when visiting a website
3. Important for SEO
4. Provides uniform starting point across servers
5. Serves as fallback when no file is specified in URL


Tags:

1. Elements that are used to crate a website are called HTML tags
2. Tags can contain content or other HTML tags
3. Define elements like text, images, links

	<p> 				welcome 			</p>
[opening tag]			[content]		  [closing tag]

[opening tag]		+	[content]	+	  [closing tag] = Element

* Using Emmet (!) to generate code

- HTML is case insensitive for tag names <html> = <HTML>
- Attribute names are also be case insensitive


HTML Attributes:
<tag attribute=“value”> Text Content </tag>
              [attribute]

- Provides additional information about elements
- Placed within opening tags
- Common examples: href, src, alt
- Use name=value format
- Can be single or multiple per element

id attribute/property:
Unique identifier: each id should be unique within a page
Anchoring: Allows for direct links to sections using the #id syntax in URLs
CSS & javascript: used for selecting elements for styling or scripting


HTML tags:
1. Heading
- <h1> to <h6>
- It doesn’t mean size instead it is considered as importance.
- <h1> is most important, <h6> is least
- Important for SEO

2. Paragraph 
- Used for defining paragraphs
- Enclosed within <p> and </p>
- Adds automatic spacing before and after
- Text wraps to next line inside tag

3. <br> tag
- <br> adds a line break within text
- <br> is empty, no closing tag needed
- <br> and </br> both are valid

4. <hr> tag
- <hr> creates a horizontal rule or line
- <br> is also empty, acts as a divider

5. Image tag
- Used to embed images
- Utilizes the ‘src’ attribute for image URL
- ‘alt’ attribute for alternative text
- Can be resized using ‘width’ and ‘height’
- Self closing, doesn’t require closing tag
- Images placed at the place where we have index.html -> relative path
- Images that we load from url [like: search for any image in google -> right click -> select copy image address -> paste it in ‘src’ attribute of image] -> absolute path

6. Video tag
- Similar to image tag
- Utilizes the ‘src’ attribute for video URL
- Supports multiple formats like MP4, WebM
- Allows for built in controls via attributes like autoplay, controls, loop

7. Anchor tag
- Used for creating hyperlinks
- Requires ‘href’ attribute for URLs
- Can link to external sites or internal pages
- Supports ‘target’ attribute to control link behaviour

8. Pre tag
- Preserves text formatting
- Maintains whitespace and line breaks
- Useful for displaying code
- Enclosed within <pre> and </pre> tags

9. Big/small tag
- <big> increases text size
- <small> decreases text size
- Less common due to CSS alternatives

10. Superscript/subscript tag
- <sup> makes text Superscript
- <sub> makes text subscript
- Used for mathematical equations and foot notes
- Does not change font size, just position

Browser tools:
1. View page source
- Displays raw HTML and CSS
- Useful for debugging and learning
- Shows external files like javascript links

2. Inspect element
- Allows real time editing of HTML/CSS
- Useful for debugging and testing
- Shows element hierarchy and layout
- Includes console for javascript
- Highlights selected element on page

3. Responsive design
- Different screen sizes
- Adapts layout for different screen sizes
- Flexible layouts
- Optimises images and assets
- Enhances user experience on mobile and desktop

4. Validating web pages
- Will use validator.w3.org
- Ensures HTMl adheres to standards
- Minimizes cross browser issues
- Helps in achieving better SEO results
- Easier to debug and maintain
- Optimises performance by reducing parsing error

Semantic tags:
- Meaningful: Correct tags used at correct places
- Good for search engines
- Accessibility: useful for screen readers
- examples: <header>, <footer>, <article>, <section>, <nav>

Non Semantic tags:
- Generic: no specific meaning
- For styling: used for layout
- Not SEO friendly
- Examples: <div>, <I>, <b>, <span>

Body tags:
- <header>
    - <nav>
- <main>
    - <section>
        - <article>
        - <article>
        - <article>
    - <section>
    - <aside>
        - <section>
        - <section>
- <footer>

Header tag:
- Purpose: use dot contain introductory content or navigation links
- It’s semantic tag
- Location: commonly found at top of webpages but can also be used inside <article>, <section> tags
- Multiple Instances: can be used more than once in webpage

Main tag:
- Purpose: encloses the primary content of webpage
- It’s semantic
- Unique: It should appear only once in webpage
- Accessibility: helps screen readers identify key content
- Not for sidebars

Section tag:
- Purpose: groups related content in distinct section
- It’s semantic
- Headers: often used with heading <h1> to <h6>
- Nested: can be nested within other <section> or <article>

Navigation tags:
- Purpose: encloses navigation links or menus
- Its semantic
- Common content: usually contains lists <ul>, <ol> of links <a>

Block elements:
- Starts on a new line
- Take up all horizontal space
- Styling: Can have margins and paddings
- Width and height can be set
- Examples: <div>, <p>, <h1>, <ul>, <li>

Inline elements:
- Stay inline with text
- Just as width as content
- No new line between elements
- Limited styling: Can’t set styles easily
- Examples: <span>, <em>, <img>

Div tags:
- Purpose: acts as a container for other html elements
- Non semantic: doesn’t provide inherent meaning to enclosed content
- Styling: commonly used for layout and styling for CSS

Span tags:
- Purpose: used for inline elements to style or manipulate a portion of text
- Non semantic: doesn’t add specific meaning to the enclosed text
- Styling: commonly used for changing colour, font or adding effects
- Inline nature

List tag:
- Ordered list
    - Used for creating lists with items that have specific order
    - Items are automatically numbered
    - Can be nested with other lists
    - Default: numbering will be 1,2,…these can be changes using different attributes, like: Attribute: type: ‘A’, type:’a’, type:’i’
- UnOrdered list
    - Used for items where order of items doesn’t matter
    - Default: items are usually bulleted
    - Can be nested with other lists

Tables:
- <tr> tag: Table row: used to define a row in HTML table
- <th> tag: Table header: used to define header cells within a row. Text is bold and centred by default
- <td> tag: Table Data: This holds the actual data
- <caption>: title for table: centre aligned
- Colspan: attribute: uses this attribute in <td> or <th> tags -> allows to span multiple cols horizontally
- 

 Hosting your website on GitHub server:
- Create GitHub account
- Github is a web service for hosting and collaborating on Git repositories.
- Create new repository
- Drag and drop all the files which you have locally
- Default branch will be ‘main’

Codespace:
- VSCode online editor
- You can edit and make changes to your code online using this codespace

Hosting/publishing:
- Host the website using GitHub pages
- Settings -> Pages -> Under build and deployment -> select branch [main] -> save
- Refresh the webpage
- You will get your site deployed: Your site is live at https://santoshtalloju.github.io/HTML_Practice/
